ce:section.ce:para:
                           Fig. 5 shows that with an increase in the concentration of EDA in a mixture of EDA and CA, the following changes occur in the bands in the IR spectra:

                                 a)

the bands of stretching vibrations of C=O (1705 cm-1) and C-O (1180 cm-1) bonds belonging to the carboxyl groups -COOH of CA [46] gradually disappear and when the EDA:CA ratio reaches 2:1, disappear completely;


                                 b)

starting from an EDA:CA ratio of 2:1 and higher, bands of stretching vibrations of NH2 (3270–3380 cm-1) and CH2 (2800–2970 cm-1), characteristic of EDA itself, appear [47];


                                 c)

with the growth of EDA:CA ratio two broad bands simultaneously appear and grow 1) with a maximum in the region of 1380 cm-1, the main contribution is symmetrical vibrations of -NO2, and 2) with a maximum in the region of 1550 cm-1 – vibrations of C=O in amides [48], asymmetrical vibrations of -NO2 (shoulder in the region of 1520 cm-1), vibrations of nitroso groups -N=O [49], deformation vibrations of amino groups -CHx, and others. Starting with the EDA:CA ratio of 4:1 the intensity of the band in the region of 1380 cm-1 and the shoulder in the region of 1520 cm-1 begins to fall: the number of -NO2 groups decreases, possibly with the transition to nitroso groups -N=O;


                                 d)

starting from an EDA:CA ratio of 2:1, a band appears at 1265 cm-1, which is then “lost” in a growing neighboring band with a maximum at 1320 cm-1, possibly belonging to C–N bonds in aromatic amines or Car-N-C;


                                 e)

starting from an EDA:CA ratio of 4:1, bands appear at 1480 and 1430 cm-1. The threshold growth of these bands after the prevalence of amino groups over carboxyl groups indicates that, most likely, they are caused by bending and stretching vibrations of C-N, N-H, C-H bonds. It is also possible that the contribution to the band at 1480 cm-1 comes from stretching vibrations of C-C bonds in aromatic rings.
